TY  - JOUR
T1  - Object-oriented software representations for statistical data
AU  - Oldford, R.Wayne
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 38
IS  - 1
SP  - 227
EP  - 246
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/05/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(88)90034-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407688900346
AB  - This paper presents new software designs for statistical data. These are implemented using an object-oriented programming paradigm. The implementations are built in a layered fashion from independent representations for the individual, variate, and datum components of a statistical observation to representations for univariate samples and multivariate observations. These in turn are combined according to a software model for an entire data set. This model is quite general and is shown to easily accomodate rather complex data sets. Statistical data-descriptive methods also separate according to the data representations and are therefore incorporated in their definition. How these data representations could be used in a new kind of statistical analysis system is also discussed. In particular, there are some strong implications for interactive statistical graphics.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Data analysis as search
AU  - Lubinsky, David
AU  - Pregibon, Daryl
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 38
IS  - 1
SP  - 247
EP  - 268
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/05/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(88)90035-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407688900358
AB  - Like a detective, a data analyst will experience many dead ends, retrace his steps, and explore many alternatives before settling on a single description of the evidence in front of him. The process of searching for this description can be as unpredictable as the data themselves. Instead of mimicking this behavior, we propose a computer system for performing an orderly search, replacing intuition and hunches (which people are good at) with extensive computation (which computers are good at). We describe a formalization of the space of descriptions used by data analysts and describe heuristics for searching through this space. The search space is characterized as an hierarchical tree, with most accurate but least parsimonious descriptions at the root of the hierarchy, and the least accurate but most parsimonious descriptions at its leaves. Using this formalization we have implemented a Tree-based Environment for developing Statistical Strategy (TESS). The system includes a development environment for implementing and evaluating statistical strategies, as well as flexible mechanisms for applying the strategies to data. We discuss this implementation and give details of a particular strategy for the task of simple regression.
ER  - 

